info:
This subflow is a filter that decodes the data structures and push the atomic data as new `dP`s.
Useful for storing atomic data in DB, it is also required to use the `RT/AVG filter` subflow, which manages only atomic data.

### Parameters
<dl class="message-properties">
    <dt>dp <span class="property-type">string</span> </dt>
    <dd>   the Data Point that produces structures
 </dd>
    <dt>decode <span class="property-type">string </span> </dt>
    <dd>   the decode function  (as in 'core.global.alldevices') for the structure.
 </dd>
 </dd> </dl>

### Input

  A message from a `tuya-smart-device` node.
  ````` 
  object
     {
    "payload": {
        "deviceId": <deviceId>,
        "data": {
            "dps": {
                "<propertyDP>":<coded_data>
            }}}
`````

### Output
  If incoming `dP` is not equal to `parameter.dp`, the msg is sent to output unchanged, else
  the output is same as input, and the data structure is decoded and the atomic data are attributed to new `dP`s added to message.
  Recursive, i.e. it accepts also structures of data structures...
  
 _note: works only on structures, not on arrays._
 _note: you must add the new atomic `dP`s to `global.alldevices`._
  
````` 
  object
     {
    "payload": {
        "deviceId": <deviceId>,
        "data": {
            "dps": {
                "<propertyDP>":<coded_data>,
                "_<propertyDP>.<pathname>":<value>,
                ... more ...
            }}}
`````
### Example
A 'Breaker_DIN' output is:

      ...    
      "dps": {    
            "6": "CNQAAGQAACIAAA==" }  // coded structure

Using the `STRUCTELERT` decode function (in `ENCODE/DECODE user library` node) we get:

          {
            V: 226
            Leack: 0
            A: 0.1
            W: 0.034
          }

The `explode` node does an early decode, and adds the required new `dP`s. The output is:

        object
          {
          "payload": {
              "deviceId": <deviceId>,
              "data": {
                  "dps": {
                      "6": "CNQAAGQAACIAAA==",  // unchanged
                      "_6.V": 226,
                      "_6.Leack": 0,
                      "_6.A": 0.1,
                      "_6.W": 0.034
              }}}

i.e. `explode` adds 4 new dPs with atomic data, as required by `RT/AWG filter` subflow.

### References
For more info [see the wiki](https://github.com/msillano/tuyaDAEMON/wiki/case-study:-433-MHz-weather-station#9-notes-about-explode-subflow).

